phbZBA ) : the founding ethos of the Internet may have been decentralizatio=
n and independence, but the economic reality of zero distribution costs was=
 inevitable centralization around Aggregators that helped users manage abun=
dance, further attracting supply, enhancing their offering, in a virtuous c=
ycle.

This effect has been, in the end, the most pronounced on the Internet, than=
ks to those zero marginal costs, where a handful of American tech companies=
 sit astride the world=E2=80=99s Internet; the glaring exception is China, =
thanks to its Great Firewall. In truth, though, this is an older and broade=
r story, for globalization has been happening for hundreds of years, and in=
 earnest over the last thirty. The loosening of trade controls, increase in=
 standardization, and the free flow of capital has massively increased retu=
rns to scale for all sectors.

Nowhere is this more pronounced than in semiconductors. We are far removed =
from the days when =E2=80=9CSilicon Valley=E2=80=9D earned its moniker, tha=
nks to the proliferation of independent chip companies that gave the area i=
ts name; now the degree of IP, tacit knowledge, and capital required to not=
 just fabricate semiconductors but also create the equipment necessary to d=
o so has led to a collection of near-monopolies who dominate chip-making, p=
articularly on the leading edge.

That, more than anything, is what makes Rapidus hard to understand: on what=
 basis can a brand new foundry challenge TSMC, when even mighty Intel is st=
ruggling? And yet, as Reidy wrote, what is the alternative? Indeed, Reidy=
=E2=80=99s conclusion in many respects is the argument for the U.S. to resc=
