One way to think about this is to consider the differences between traditio=
nal and digital advertising. Traditional advertising was monetized on a uni=
t basis; an ad agency took a cut of the placement cost for a television or =
newspaper ad, while the overall budget was pre-determined. Digital advertis=
ing, however, is outcome-based: you buy based on results, and if it=E2=80=
=99s working, you buy more; the entire process is automated. Imagine the sa=
me shift in enterprise-relevant outcomes: instead of pricing based on seats=
, the holders of which do the job in question, AI will be priced on outcome=
s; the better it does the more usage will be purchased.

This will take time, to be sure, and proceed in some manner of fits and sta=
rts. It may be the case that the most economically momentous outcomes will,=
