There is no better time to be a forecaster than when demand exceed supply, =
because supply is more easily understandable and predictable; Apple=E2=80=
=99s forecasters for the first eight or so years of the iPhone weren=E2=80=
=99t geniuses, they just understood that as Apple brought the iPhone to new=
 carriers, complete with guaranteed sales contracts, they knew to a high de=
gree of accuracy how many iPhones they would sell. The moment that iPhones =
were available everywhere, however, was the moment that Apple=E2=80=99s for=
ecasting accuracy plummeted.

The Nvidia analogy is that, as long as demand exceeds supply, projections a=
re easy; it gets a lot harder when demand is uncertain. And the analogy I=
=E2=80=99m making here is to my analysis: a world where everything is gover=
ned by economics is, in the end, an easier world to understand; one in whic=
h decisions are made in defiance of them, for political reasons or whatever=
 else, is more difficult. It=E2=80=99s like the shift from deterministic co=
mputing to probabilistic AI: uncertainty is both the risk and the opportuni=
ty, and things are more uncertain than ever.

